english:
  title: Reply to Satari's Letter
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly submit this response. Last month, on such and such a day, I suddenly received your esteemed letter, and learning that your health and all circumstances are in perfect order has brought me joy beyond measure. Regarding your instruction to send correspondence to the Emperor, I have attended to each matter as directed and have already prepared the formal memorial. I shall dispatch an envoy shortly and trust you will take note of this.

    Our country, as mentioned in my previous letter, though dwelling in fear of the great power and secluded among mountains and seas, remains steadfast in our reverence and service to the imperial court with an unchanging heart. For this reason, hearing that your great army crosses our borders, I promptly sent an envoy to perform the rites of welcome and inquiry with utmost respect. Upon receiving your subsequent letter, I sent emissaries bearing humble gifts of wine and fruit as tokens of our esteem, thereby demonstrating our nation's unwavering loyalty. For we serve with a single heart, and the matter transcends considerations of territorial distance. I earnestly beseech you not to regard our relocation as a transgression, but to treat us as before. This alone would be an eternal blessing for our small nation.

    The envoys I send to the Emperor shall first present themselves at your headquarters to receive instructions. The fate of these emissaries—their advancement or retreat, their actions, and indeed their fortune or misfortune, life or death—all rest within your grasp. I humbly implore you to extend your protection and guidance with utmost care, and moreover, to dispatch officers from your retinue to conduct them safely to the Emperor's palace, thus eternally safeguarding our modest realm. How could I fail to inscribe such kindness upon my very bones?

    As for the matter of the great official's prostration before us, our small nation, already anxious in this remote and secluded place, finds even our officials diminished in spirit—growing ever more clumsy with each passing day and duller with each passing month. We have not yet managed to hasten to your side to receive your commands. Overwhelmed with apprehension and confusion, we know not what course to take. I beseech you alone to extend your magnanimity and pardon. My gratitude for your benevolence surpasses all bounds and exceeds what words can express. With much left unsaid, I bow twice in deepest respect.
  footnotes:
    - Satari (사타리) refers to a Mongol official or commander; this letter is a response to correspondence from Mongol representatives.
    - The references to 'great army,' 'Emperor,' and 'imperial court' reflect Koryŏ's complex relationship with the Mongol Yuan Dynasty during the 13th century.
    - Lee Gyu-bo (1168-1241) was a prominent Koryŏ scholar-official and poet who engaged in diplomatic correspondence during the Mongol invasions.
